Correlation

In order to test the assumptions of linearity and multicollinearity, we start with a correlation analysis of all possible pairs of variables. The matrix scatterplots and correlation coefficients below inform us of:

  • Are all relationships between the predictor variables and the outcome variables, linear? -> linearity
  • Are there any strong relationships between the predictor variables? -> multicollinearity
  • Do we see any extreme values in the scatterplots? -> sensitivity

Pearson's r heatmap

The heatmap presents a quick overview of the strenghts of the associations between the variables. While we find no strong relationships between the predictor variables, there is a strong association between study and grade, and alcohol and grade.


Linear Regression

The linear regression below shows the predictive quality of the various predictor variables:

Model Summary & ANOVA table:

  • How much more variance does the alternative model explain, compared to the null model?
  • The F and R2 change values indicate whether the variables that are added in the alternative model, lead to significancly better predictions
  • F and R2 do not have a strong built-in parsimony: models that predict better will usually be rewarded here, even if model complexity is much greater. (Parsimony = Occam's razor; we want to predict as good as possible, with as few predictors as possible).

Coefficients table:

  • For each predictor in the model, what are we estimating as their regression coefficients?
  • The slope coefficients inform us what/how the model predicts (and those predictions then get use to asses model performance)
  • We can test whether these coefficients deviate significantly from 0 by converting them to t-statistics (the t-statistics have a well-defined sampling distribution).
  • When "collinearity diagnostics" is enabled, this table lists Tolerance and VIF for each predictor, which helps to assess multicollinearity

The casewise diagnostics below list the row numbers of "influential" observations. We can ask JASP to give the row numbers for all cases that meet some sort of criterion. We can either base this on standardized residual, Cook's distance, or both. For instance, if we set the residual threshold to 3, it will list all obesrvations where the prediction error is greater than 3 standard deviations; this can be an indication of an outlier.

The plot below, standardized residuals vs predicted. allows us to assess the homoscedasticity assumption:

  • are the prediction errors fairly constant across the whole range of what we predict?
  • If yes, great!
  • If no, then our model is biased (e.g., it will systematically under- or over-estimated for high/low predicted values), and it should be interpreted cautiously.
